SIMPLE: score
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Score
<hw>Score</hw> <pr>(sk⟦omac⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>scor</ets> twenty, fr. <ets>sceran</ets>, <ets>scieran</ets>, to
shear, cut, divide; or rather the kindred Icel. <ets>skor</ets>
incision, twenty, akin to Dan. <ets>skure</ets> a notch, Sw.
<ets>sk⟦aring⟧ra</ets>. See <er>Shear</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
notch or incision; especially, one that is made as a tally mark; hence,
a mark, or line, made for the purpose of account.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whereas, before, our forefathers had no other books but the
<qex>score</qex> and the tally, thou hast caused printing to be
used.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An account or reckoning; account of dues; bill;
hence, indebtedness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He parted well, and paid his <qex>score</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Account; reason; motive; sake; behalf.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But left the trade, as many more⟦br⟧
Have lately done on the same <qex>score</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You act your kindness in Cydaria's <qex>score</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The number twenty, as being marked off by a special
score or tally; hence, in <pluf>pl.</pluf>, a large number.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Amongst three or four <qex>score</qex> hogsheads.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At length the queen took upon herself to grant patents of monopoly
by <qex>scores</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A distance of twenty yards; -- a term used in
ancient archery and gunnery.</def> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A weight of twenty pounds.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The number of points gained by the contestants, or
either of them, in any game, as in cards or cricket.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A line drawn; a groove or furrow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The original and entire draught,
or its transcript, of a composition, with the parts for all the
different instruments or voices written on staves one above another, so
that they can be read at a glance; -- so called from the bar, which, in
its early use, was drawn through all the parts.</def> <rj><au>Moore
(Encyc. of Music).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>the grade received on an examination, such as those
given in school or as a qualifying examination for a job or admission to
school; -- it may be expressed as a percentage of answers which are
correct, or as a number or letter; <as>as, a <ex>score</ex> of 98 in a
civil service exam</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>In score</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>having all the
parts arranged and placed in juxtaposition.</cd> <au>Smart.</au> --
<col><b>To quit scores</b></col>, <cd>to settle or balance accounts; to
render an equivalent; to make compensation.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Does not the earth <qex>quit scores</qex> with all the elements in
the noble fruits that issue from it?</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Score</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Score
<hw>Score</hw> <pr>(sk⟦omac⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Scored</conjf> <pr>(sk⟦omac⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Scoring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To mark
with lines, scratches, or notches; to cut notches or furrows in; to
notch; to scratch; to furrow; <as>as, to <ex>score</ex> timber for
hewing; to <ex>score</ex> the back with a lash</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us <qex>score</qex> their backs.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A briar in that tangled wilderness⟦br⟧
Had <qex>scored</qex> her white right hand.</q> <rj><qau>M.
Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Especially, to mark with significant lines or
notches, for indicating or keeping account of something; <as>as, to
<ex>score</ex> a tally</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To mark or signify by lines or notches; to keep
record or account of; to set down; to record; to charge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Madam, I know when,⟦br⟧
Instead of five, you <qex>scored</qex> me ten.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor need I tallies thy dear love to <qex>score</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To engrave, as upon a shield.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To make a score of, as points, runs, etc., in a
game.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To write down in proper order and
arrangement; <as>as, to <ex>score</ex> an overture for an
orchestra</as>. See <er>Score</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 9.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>To mark with parallel lines or
scratches; <as>as, the rocks of New England and the Western States were
<ex>scored</ex> in the drift epoch</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Score</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Score
<hw>Score</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To keep
the score in a game; to act as scorer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make or count a point or points, as in a game; to
tally.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To run up a score, or account of dues.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To succeed in finding a partner for sexual
intercourse; to make a sexual conquest.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To purchase drugs illegally.</def>
<mark>[slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scorer</ent>⟦br⟧
